Hey everyone. If you add   newVideoLoaded(); at the end of contentScript as the purposed quick fix, the extension won't work properly on reload. The reason is that you will not get the video ID into the currentVideo variable, so you won't be able to add new timestamps. The best quick fix I came up with was to force a new URL (I also studied how YouTube deals with different URLs) and I came up with this code that you can add to your contentScript in the place of newVideoLoaded() (the one at the end, line 64 of the finished code);

let trail="&ytExt=ON";
if(!window.location.href.includes(trail)&&!window.location.href.includes("ab_channel")){
        window.location.href+=trail;
   }

This should force an update on the URL of the YouTube when necessary, which will then trigger the chrome.tabs.onUpdated. I hope this helps. (For those who want to know what is ab_channel, it is something youtube adds spontaneously for some videos (with channel info) and that triggers the chrome.tabs.onUpdated on its own.) Cheers!

EDIT!!

Also include a condition &&window.location.href.includes("youtube.com/watch") in the if statement i gave. You don't want it to update the URL in non-YouTube websites.
